%N A387833 sqrt(a(n)) / 4 is the maximum area of any triangle with integer side lengths whose perimeter is n, or a(n) = -1 if there is no such triangle.
%C A387833 This includes degenerate triangles with an edge of length 0, for which the area is 0. If they are excluded, then a(n) = -1 for n = 0, 2, and 4.
%C A387833 There is a unique triangle of maximum area (modulo isometries) for all n except n = 1, which has no valid triangles, and n = 4, which has no triangles of positive area and two distinct degenerate triangles of area 0 with side lengths (0, 2, 2) and (1, 1, 2). For all other n, the unique maximum area triangle has side lengths (m, m, m) when n = 3m, (m, m, m + 1) when n = 3m + 1, and (m, m + 1, m + 1) when n = 3m + 2.
%H A387833 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A387833/b387833.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A387833 <a href="/index/Rec#order_11">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (2,-1,3,-6,3,-3,6,-3,1,-2,1).
%F A387833 a(3m + 0) = 3m^4.
%F A387833 a(3m + 1) = 3m^4 + 4m^3 - 2m^2 - 4m - 1.
%F A387833 a(3m + 2) = 3m^4 + 8m^3 + 4m^2.
%e A387833 For n = 3, there is a unique triangle (modulo isometries) with integer side lengths and perimeter n. It is an equilateral triangle with sides of length 1, and it has area sqrt(3) / 4. Therefore, a(3) = 3.
%e A387833 For n = 7, there are two such triangles, given by side lengths (1, 3, 3) and (2, 2, 3). The first has area sqrt(35) / 4 and the second sqrt(63) / 4. Therefore, a(7) = 63.
%e A387833 For n = 11, there are four such triangles, given by side lengths (1, 5, 5), (2, 4, 5), (3, 3, 5), and (3, 4, 4). The corresponding areas are sqrt(99) / 4, sqrt(231) / 4, sqrt(275) / 4, and sqrt(495) / 4. Therefore, a(11) = 495.
%t A387833 A387833[n_] := 3*#^4 + Switch[Mod[n, 3], 0, 0, 1, 4*#^3 - 2*#^2 - 4*# - 1, _, 8*#^3 + 4*#^2] & [Quotient[n, 3]];
